# Fix, Don't Remove

## Golden rule

**Never remove or disable a user-facing feature** (3D backgrounds, nav transitions, showcase, SiteBackground, TransitionLink, etc.) without **explicit user approval**.

If something breaks → **diagnose and fix**, do not strip it out as a shortcut.

## Required workflow when something fails

1. **Reproduce** — identify route, browser, error (WebGL, console, layout).
2. **Root cause** — z-index, pointer-events, remount, SSR, texture load, scroll lock, etc.
3. **Minimal targeted fix** — smallest change that restores behavior.
4. **Keep fallbacks** — `BackgroundErrorBoundary`, CSS fallback, `SafeCanvas`, showcase phases must stay.
5. **Verify** — `npm run type-check && npm run build`; smoke-test affected routes.
6. **Deploy** — push only after build passes.
7. **Simplify or remove** — only if user explicitly asks, never as a silent workaround.

## Pre-merge checklist (site + showcase)

- [ ] Main nav links clickable (backgrounds `pointer-events-none`, content `z-[1]`)
- [ ] Scroll not permanently locked after transitions
- [ ] Per-route 3D backgrounds visible (or CSS fallback if no WebGL)
- [ ] `/portfolio-showcase` has no Header/Footer/SiteBackground; phases mutually exclusive
- [ ] Nav transitions still work on main nav (TransitionLink paths only)
- [ ] No new always-on `fixed inset-0` layers without gating existing ones

## Forbidden without user permission

- Removing `SiteBackground`, `PageBackgroundCanvas`, or route-specific `*Background.tsx`
- Disabling `PageTransitionProvider` / overlay because of a bug
- Replacing WebGL with static CSS only (fallback path is OK; primary canvas must remain)
- Removing showcase joystick, HUD, or 3D room to "fix" performance
- Commenting out broken code instead of fixing it

